<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>TEMPERED PENALTIES FOR GUILTY PLEAS</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> For banks, a guilty plea in a felony case is the equivalent of a scarlet letter, one that could lead to a revoked license in the worst-case scenario. But for the five big banks that are expected to plead guilty to conspiring to manipulate foreign currency rates, life will go on, âprobably without much of a hiccup,â <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/05/14/business/dealbook/5-big-banks-expected-to-plead-guilty-to-felony-charges-but-punishments-may-be-tempered.html">Ben Protess and Michael Corkery write in DealBook</a>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As soon as next week, the Justice Department will announce that Barclays, JPMorgan Chase, Citigroup and the Royal Bank of Scotland will collectively pay several billion dollars and plead guilty to antitrust violations, according to people briefed on the matter. The guilty pleas represent a milestone in prosecutorsâ broader crackdown on financial crimes, Mr. Protess and Mr. Corkery write: Most if not all of the pleas are expected to come <b>from the banksâ holding companies, which is a first.</b> Until now, the major banks have had only subsidiaries or their biggest banking units plead guilty. Also, the Justice Department is taking the rare step of <b>revoking a nonprosecution agreement with UBS</b> over the manipulation of benchmark interest rates because of the bankâs foreign currency misconduct, the people said. This action underscores the threats that department officials have made about voiding past deals in the event of new misdeeds.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Yet prosecutors are aware that an overly harsh penalty could harm the banks that are at the heart of the global economy, âa balancing act that could produce pleas that are more symbolic than sweeping,â Mr. Protess and Mr. Corkery write. At the same time, the banksâ lawyers are seeking assurances from federal regulators in Washington that the banks will not be barred from certain business practices after the guilty pleas. The people briefed on the matter expected <b>a majority of the Securities and Exchange Commissionâs five commissioners to grant waivers</b> to allow the banks to conduct business as usual despite being felons. <b>âIn reality, those accommodations render the plea deals, at least in part, an exercise in stagecraft,â</b> Mr. Protess and Mr. Corkery write.<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>LESSONS FROM DUPONT BATTLE</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Shareholder activism suffered a defeat on Wednesday after the billionaire Nelson Peltz and his firm, Trian Fund Management, failed to gain a board seat at DuPont, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/05/14/business/dealbook/nelson-peltzs-slate-fails-to-win-dupont-board-seats.html">Michael J. de la Merced writes in DealBook</a>. What Trianâs failure means for the future of shareholder activism is uncertain, but for shareholder activist battles, there are lessons in the way DuPont and Trian both won and lost, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/05/14/business/dealbook/in-the-dupont-boardroom-battle-sizing-up-who-won-and-lost.html">Steven Davidoff Solomon writes in the Deal Professor column</a>. Among them: </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Narrative matters</b>: DuPont is, by many measures, not a broken company where shareholders are unhappy with performance, but Trian tried to portray DuPont as not achieving its full potential. âThis took away Trianâs head start, making it a more uphill battle,â Professor Solomon writes. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b> Clarity counts</b>: There was no clarity over how badly DuPont was doing given that it was a company in transition helped by an aggressive chief executive who seeks change. Both sides seemed to spend too much time arguing over what time periods to count and which businesses to evaluate, rather than whether the company was actually doing a bad job. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Losing can be winning</b>: In the long run, the fight with Trian has forced DuPont to vigorously argue and refine its strategy. âThis may not be the strategy that Trian wants, but it is probably better than where DuPont was before,â Professor Solomon writes. âMoreover, Trian may or may not go away. DuPont knows this. Its influence will remain as long as it is an owner.â<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>A BANK VETERAN AT LENDING START-UP </strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Jerry Weiss is used to the youth culture that reigns at Bond Street, the start-up small-business lender he joined last year. His two bosses are 27 and 33, and his younger colleagues make fun of his New Balance sneakers and âdad jeans.â Still, Mr. Weiss offers value to alternative lenders like Bond Street: Heâs a grizzled veteran who has lived through downturns and has learned what can go wrong, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/05/14/business/dealbook/for-lending-start-up-a-man-whos-been-through-a-few-cycles.html">Randall Smith writes in DealBook</a>. Mr. Weiss, who has worked at Citigroup and JPMorgan Chase, said, âI have seen many online lenders who are bringing in some bright young people into the role I am doing, but they are folks who have never made a loan in their lives.â He added, âThey think itâs all science and math, but theyâve never been through a recession.â </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The appeal of the start-up was clear, he said, recalling how he used to be stuck in âendless meetings and endless levels of approvals for everythingâ at the big banks. <b>âI wanted to break free and have fun again,â</b> he said. He recognizes the risk of alternative lending, bringing a distinctive quantitative approach to the business, but he also values personal contact with applicants to gauge their path to profitability. On one call, Mr. Weiss asked about a shop ownerâs latest tax filings and QuickBooks updates, and about a new baby, who was audible in the background. âCustomers like talking to the chief credit officer,â he said after the call. âAnd I love hearing their stories.â<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ON THE AGENDA</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The Labor Department will release data on <b>weekly jobless claims</b> and the <b>April producer price index</b> at 8:30 a.m. <b>Applied Materials, Kohlâs, Nordstrom and Symantec</b> are among the companies reporting earnings today. <b>Mario Draghi</b>, the president of the European Central Bank, will speak at the International Monetary Fund in Washington at 11 a.m. <b>Carson Block</b>, founder of Muddy Waters Research, is on Bloomberg Television at 12:05 p.m. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b> On the Hill</b>: The House Financial Services Committee will hold a hearing titled âProtecting Consumers: Financial Data Security in the Age of Computer Hackersâ at 10 a.m.<br />
</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>$229 MILLION PRICE TAG TO FULFILL PROMISE</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The founder of GoPro, Nick Woodman, took a $229 million hit to his fortune this week to fulfill a promise made to his college roommate when the company was in the developmental phase, <a href="//www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-05-13/gopro-billionaire-returns-229-million-to-satisfy-10-year-vow">Bloomberg News reports</a>. The back story: Mr. Woodman, 39, promised to give Neil Dana, his roommate at the University of California at San Diego and the first GoPro employee, 10 percent of any proceeds he received from the sale of the companyâs shares, according to the companyâs 2014 prospectus. To cancel this agreement, GoPro issued Mr. Dana <b>more than 6 million fully vested options</b> in June 2011 and 270,000 restricted stock units six months later. Mr. Woodman agreed to reimburse the company when the options were exercised. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Dana, who is GoProâs director of music and specialty sales, spent $3.6 million to exercise his options, according to data compiled by Bloomberg. They were valued at $229 million at the close of trading on Monday. The GoPro founder returned 4.7 million shares to the company on May 11, according to a regulatory filing. Now <b>his net worth will fall to a mere $2.3 billion</b>, according to the Bloomberg Billionaires Index. </p>
